<Layout title="Avoiding Pearling - Surf Deeper" description="Learn to prevent nose diving and pearling when catching waves. Master positioning, speed, and board control to stay on top of the wave.">
  <header class="page-header">
    <h1>Avoiding Pearling</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">Stay on top of the wave, not under it</p>
  </header>

  <article class="technique-article">
    <section class="introduction">
      <h2>Why Pearling Happens</h2>
      <p>Pearlingâ€”when your board's nose dives under the waterâ€”is one of the most frustrating experiences in surfing. You're perfectly positioned, the wave looks perfect, and suddenly you're underwater instead of riding. Understanding why it happens is the first step to preventing it.</p>
      
      <p>Pearling occurs when your board's nose gets caught by the wave's energy before the tail does. This happens when you're too far forward on the board, going too slow, or taking off too late. The wave's steep face catches your nose and pulls it down, while your tail is still on the flatter part of the wave.</p>
      
